data.title: A Piece Of Havana In The East Bay
data.text:
This, my first  trip to Alameda was a total surprise as I did not expect to discover a very nice community of restaurants and shopping to suit all tastes.

Habanas, was the perfect place to celebrate a family member's birthday. 

The welcoming friendly staff could not have been more pleasant. Once crossing the portal from the sidewalk, be prepared to be transported to a piece of Havana. Wonderful murals and photographs line the walls in this casual dining room with lively Cuban music playing in the background. I could not help but tap my foot and keep beat with the exotic melodies.

The menu offers a good selection of classic tapas, warm Cuban pressed sandwiches, sides, entrees and desserts. Soft drinks and full bar round out the dining experience.

data.title: Nice family meal
data.text: Recommended by the owner of the house we were renting nearby we decided to give this a try. Good cocktails . Friendly,speedy service. Delicious food including tapas and salads and hot sandwiches. The children all enjoyed it and raved over the homemade fries. Good value.

data.title: authentic
data.text: we always share the tapa plates so many choices the sea scallops and the plantain dishes are our go to plates also try the white and red sangrias

data.title: Great food and reasonable
data.text: My husband catches his own fish and takes it to Habanas and they prepare a great fish.  The sides are amazing and it's plenty of food.  The plantains and tostones are really good.  Good for families, kids and large groups.

data.title: Expensive
data.text: The food was good, the restaurant rather plain, music too loud, you can not visit with your friends unless you yell. Very busy, staff friendly but expensive for what you get $81 for 2 people and not fine dining

data.title: Best Cuban food ever
data.text: My son took my wife and I to this rather unpretentious restaurant in Alameda and we all loved it.  The mango gazpacho was a great start, day boat scallops (5) were seared just right and served in a good sauce, my wifes halibut was fresh and cooked just right and the corn side was excellent.  Only thing that got an only "very good" was the flan perhaps because we were too full

data.title: Happy Hour $5 Mojitos
data.text: Quick, easy stop in for a cocktail before dinner as we saw the Happy Hour sign. A dozen different Mojitos to choose from - bartender was helpful & nice without being overly friendly. Place was practically empty at 5 PM though .... Didn't try any food but Mojitos were refreshing and tasty. Happy Hour was 3 - 6.

data.title: Over priced with sub-par service.
data.text: Despite the previous reviews might depict, the cuisine was hugely overpriced in conjunction with the quality of the food and service. The waitress/server was not knowledgeable of the menu or the ingredients in the dishes. That could've been acceptable if she was willing to inquire with someone more knowledgeable, the cooks/chefs, etc. My wife and I assumed that was obvious next step, but before we knew it, the dish was being served. The dish was not worth the price being advertised, nor was the service. AND WE LOVE CUBAN FOOD!

data.title: Tapas and Sangria
data.text:
We only stopped in for a small bite and a drink, so I can't comment on much of the menu, but what we had (beef empanadas and sangria) was really yummy. My husband and I ordered one red sangria and one white. The red was much better because they make the white fresh vs. letting the wine sit in the fruit for a while. 

The empanada was delicious and was a nice sized portion. The aioli sauce on top was super yummy although it did overpower the rest of the flavors a bit. It was mid afternoon on a Sunday when we were there so it wasn't very busy, but I can see it being a lively place for a dinner and bar scene kind of place. The service was really friendly and it had a nice vibe. I'd love to go back for a full dinner and to try the Cuban sandwich.

data.title: Good Business Lunch in Alameda
data.text: Very good Cuban dishes with super fine service.  The local fish of the day, that day was halibut, is always a reliable choice as well as the Cubano sandwiches.

data.title: Interesting
data.text: Love Cuban food and thought this place had most of the decor down, but the food was "kinda" Cuban. Pretty good. But after living in south Florida for 40 years I'm pretty sure the chef has been given a lot of liberty with the recipes. Roast pork good-bowl of strange grease it sat in was not so much. Bread was horrible. Please use fresh bread. No chicken soup. So sad. There was something off on all the dishes, not necessarily bad, but really strange. And no side of black beans and rice. Really? No plantains? Hope they freak the recipes. I'll still go back.

data.title: Bad food, drinks, service in 2015
data.text:
several years ago in 2010 or so I had a magical experience at Habana listening to Cuban music by a creative duo while eating mussels and calamari and drinking mojitos.  I returned last night to a most disappointing transformation.

First, we were one of three, two-person  tables seated. So it's a slow night.  Still, service was so slow and intermittent.  The rum drink we ordered was so sour it made my mouth hurt.  We sent them back and he returned with the exact same bad drinks.  We ordered calamari that was so salty we couldn't eat it.  Literally!  Not just "oh this is decadent but ill indulge" type salty.  This was inedible salty.

Then ropa vieja empanadas.  Hard dry tasteless exterior, tiny bit of meat inside.  Then a ceviche.  Runny overly sweet sauce, little fish.  Not terrible, but not good.

15 minutes we'd wait after we ate a tapas for the next one.  Terrible, novice service.  Doesn't cut it on park street in alameda.  Many good options on that strip that far outshine this restaurant that I so loved in years past.  Not sure what happened.  Darn! an expensive meal with little to show for it.

data.title: Fantastic food find!
data.text: Loved dining here! Great decor, food , music and service. Relished the Plantain Crusted Halibut and Paella. Felt like we were "away on a vacation" for the evening!

data.title: Nice Little Cuba restuarant
data.text: Out for a "date night" after and evening movie. Atmosphere was just right, food was good,given a nice spot which gave us some degree of privacy. Actually able to have a conversation. Been there before and can be a bit noisy when crowded, so lucked out. Waiter was friendly and serves was good.

data.title: Worth it.
data.text: Fun cusine, relaxed atmosphere and great pricing. One of Alameda's coolest restaurants.  We stop in here mid-week and have never had to wait for seating.

data.title: Try try try it!
data.text: Nice restaurant. Food is good although you would think food would be bland or spicy! Nice music adds to the atmosphere.

data.title: Hit or miss
data.text: This place is either the best place ever or you feel robbed, I guess it all depends on your luck. Halibut is very good most od the times. Same can be said about skirt steak. Only thing that is consistently good is grilled corn.

data.title: Excellent Cubano food
data.text:
The service is punctilious and the food superb. They make the best mojito I have ever had in a restaurant.

The only problem is that the music (which is generally quite good but blasts out the open doors) is sometimes too loud for comfortable conversation.

data.title: Not bad
data.text: First time at this reataurant and I found it just average. We ordered the mixed grill, plantains, and the paella.  Of the three, the mixed grill was probably the best. The fried plantains lacked any flavor even with the salsa and the paella wasn't very authentic.  Service was at least good and friendly.

data.title: we took a chance...
data.text: Our second time in Alameda so we wanted to try somewhere we hadn't been before.  My wife found Habana on the internet a noticed they served food 'tapas' style.  Big doors were open to the street and some musicians were playing live music with cuban rhythm.  Nice simple decor, lots of room between tables.  the menu was good, service was friendly.  we ate a lot of good food. They claim the  "best Mojito's in the east bay." i wouldn't argue.  we'd go again.
